Memory.MEM2: Gabe Martinez is a Republican, I'm sure, and seems very conservative with both social and economic policies. He does not support abortion, marriage equality, or raising taxes for the wealthy. He spouts religious rhetoric. Thus, there's no chance I would vote for him.
Memory.MEM3: John Wendell seems educated and intelligent, if a little pompous. I agree with his social policies 100%, but I don't agree that entitlements shouldn't be re-evaluated. He's probably a Democrat, though it's possible he's an independent as well.

Memory.MEM1: Huskins was sort of the "middle of the road" candidate, though in a real Republican primary, he'd probably be the leftward-most of the bunch.  His views are fudged or "evolved" on gun control, climate change, gay marriage, taxes, and healthcare.  He's from Louisiana but born in Texas and is a House member.  He's been married to Lydia for 32 years.  He takes the "personally pro-life" position on abortion and hedges on gay marriage but indicates no firm opposition.   He's in favor of some new restrictions on gun rights, probably including background checks.  He is a strong supporter of Israel and seems strong overall on foreign policy.  He argues for the need to reform entitlements but hedges a little on taxes.  On religious freedom, he's clear that the governments should not force private businesses to pay for contraception against their conscience.  He opposed Obamacare but accepts the law now that it is in places.  He supports allowing teachers to question evolution in public schools.
Memory.MEM2: Marco Rubio with a different name and face (and fictional divorce: Martinez is married to his second wife Melanie, with three children between the two marriages).  Down-the-line conservative on every issue except perhaps immigration (like Rubio himself).  Strongly influenced by Catholic background; now in Florida but has lived in several states.  Emphasizes entitlement reform and cutting spending; strong supporter of War on Terror; supports traditional marriage and is strongly pro-life.  Supports repeal of Obamacare, the rights of businesses to follow their conscience in providing insurance coverage; supports gun rights, the repeal of campaign finance restrictions, and questioning evolution in public schools.  Questions climate change.  Supports the Florida Seminoles.
Memory.MEM3: Wendell is from New Hampshire.  He is the oldest of the candidates.  I'm not sure what he is doing in a Republican primary at all; even for New England he's a liberal.  He supports gay marriage and abortion (without the "personally pro-life" language), accepts Obamacare and the concept behind the HHS mandate.  He accepts new gun restrictions and opposes any discussion of opposing theories of origin in the public schools.  He is open to raising taxes for those making over 400,000 a year.  (In any sort of a real Republican primary, that alone would doom him.)  He supports a path to citizenship for illegals.  He was once convicted of driving under the influence and hit a parked car.
